Definition 2.19. A map $f:S\to T$ of truncation posets is an $N$-map ($N$ for norm) if it satisfies the following additional conditions. (1) For every $s\in S$ and $t^{\prime}\in T$ with $t^{\prime}$ in the same connected component as $f(s)$ there exists an $s^{\prime}\in S$ in the same connected component as $s$ with $t^{\prime}\mid f(s^{\prime})$. (2) For every $t\in T$ the set $\widehat{f^{-1}}(t)=\textnormal{minimal elements of }\{s\in S\quad|\quad t\mid f% (s)\}$ is finite.
Definition 5.7. Let $S\xrightarrow{f}A\xleftarrow{g}T$ be a diagram with $f\in\mathcal{TP}^{N}$ and $g\in\mathcal{TP}^{R}$, and suppose the pullback $f_{\otimes}^{*}T$ exists. Then we declare the composite $g^{*}\circ f_{\otimes}$ to be equal to the composite $f^{\prime}_{\otimes}\circ(g^{\prime})^{*}$.
Definition 2.3. Let $S$ be a truncation poset and let $k$ be a commutative ring. The $S$-Witt vectors of $k$, denoted $\mathbb{W}_{S}(k)$, is the set $k^{S}$. The ghost map is the map $w:\mathbb{W}_{S}(k)\to k^{S}$ sending the vector $(a_{s})$ to the vector $\langle x_{s}\rangle$ with $x_{s}=\sum_{t\mid s}|t|a_{t}^{s/t}.$
Definition 6.1. Let $\mathcal{TP}^{TNR}_{\textnormal{join}}$ be the category whose objects are truncation posets with join, and whose morphisms are generated by equivalence classes of morphisms of truncation posets with join in the same way as in Definition 5.1.
Definition 4.1. The category $\mathcal{TP}^{TR}$ has objects the truncation posets, and a morphism $S\to T$ in $\mathcal{TP}^{TR}$ is an equivalence class of diagrams $S\overset{f_{1}}{\longrightarrow}A_{1}\overset{f_{2}}{\longrightarrow}A_{2}% \overset{f_{3}}{\longrightarrow}\ldots\overset{f_{n}}{\longrightarrow}A_{n}% \overset{f_{n+1}}{\longrightarrow}T$ where each $f_{i}$ is a map in one of $\mathcal{TP}^{T}$ and $(\mathcal{TP}^{R})^{\mathrm{op}}$. The equivalence relation on such diagrams is generated by the following types of relations: (1) Isomorphism of diagrams. (2) Insertion of an identity morphism. (3) Composition if $f_{i}$ and $f_{i+1}$ are in the same category $\mathcal{TP}^{T}$ or $(\mathcal{TP}^{R})^{\mathrm{op}}$. (4) Commuting an $R$-map past a $T$-map as in Definition 4.2 below.
Definition 3.2. Let $f:S\to T$ be a map of truncation posets. Then $f^{*}:\mathbb{W}_{T}(k)\to\mathbb{W}_{S}(k)$ is defined to be the unique map, functorial in $k$, such that the diagram $\xymatrix{\mathbb{W}_{T}(k)\ar[r]^{-}w\ar[d]_{f^{*}}&k^{T}\ar[d]^{f^{*}_{w}}\\ \mathbb{W}_{S}(k)\ar[r]^{-}w&k^{S}}$ commutes. Here $f^{*}_{w}$ is defined by $(f^{*}_{w}\langle x_{t}\rangle)_{s}=x_{f(s)}$.
Definition 5.4. We say the pullback $f^{*}_{\otimes}T$ from Definition 5.3 exists (as a truncation poset) if the following additional condition is satisfied. For any $(s_{1},t_{1},\xi_{1})$ and $(s_{2},t_{2},\xi_{2})$ in $f^{*}_{\otimes}T$ with $s_{1}$ and $s_{2}$ in the same connected component of $S$ and $t_{1}$ and $t_{2}$ in the same connected component of $T$ we have $|s_{1}||t_{2}|=|s_{2}||t_{1}|$. We then define $|(s,t,\xi)|=\gcd(|s|,|t|)$ and $(s_{1},t_{1},\xi_{1})\mid(s_{2},t_{2},\xi_{2})\qquad\textnormal{if}\qquad s_{1% }\mid s_{2},t_{1}\mid t_{2}\textnormal{ and }\xi_{1}=\xi_{2},$ where as usual we have identified $C_{m_{1}}$ and $C_{m_{2}}$.
Definition 3.5. The semi-derived Hall algebra of the pair $(\mathcal{F},\mathcal{P(F)})$ is the localization of $\mathcal{H(C)}$ at the classes of all projective-injective objects: $\mathcal{SDH(F,P(F))}:=\mathcal{H(F)}[[P]^{-1}|P\in\mathcal{P(F)}].$
Definition 3.7 Let $CC$ be a C-system. A closed model of $CC$ is a collection of data of the following form: 1. A category $\cal C$, 2. a universe $p:\widetilde{U}\rightarrow U$ in $\cal C$ and a final object $pt$ of $\cal C$, 3. a C-system morphism $CC\rightarrow CC({\cal C},p)$.
Definition 2.1 Let $\cal C$ be a category. A universe on $\cal C$ is a morphism $p:\widetilde{U}\rightarrow U$ together with a mapping which assigns to any morphism $f:X\rightarrow U$ in $\cal C$ a pull-back square $\lx@ams@matrix@{name=CD,datameaning=commutative-diagram}(X,f)@>{Q(f)}>{}>% \widetilde{U}\\ @V{p_{(X,f)}}V{}V@V{}V{p}V\\ X@>{f}>{}>U$
Definition 7.1. Consider the set $[n]=\{\,0,\dots,n\,\}$, for any non-negative integer $n$. The simplicial category, denoted by $\Delta$, is the category for which the objects are the sets $[n]$ and the morphisms are order preserving maps. The semi-simplicial category, denoted by $\Delta_{+}$, is the full subcategory of $\Delta$ containing only the injective (strictly monotone) functions. A simplicial set (or a $\Delta$-set) is a presheaf $\Omega:\Delta^{op}\rightarrow Set$, and a semi-simplicial set (or a $\Delta_{+}$-set) is a presheaf $\Omega:\Delta_{+}^{op}\rightarrow Set$.
Definition 7.5. Let $X$ be a semi-simplicial set. It is well known that the topoi in which subterminal objects generate are exactly the localic topoi (cf. [23]). This is the case of $\widehat{{\mathcal{H}}}$. We can form the semi-simplicial ${\mathcal{H}}$-sheaf $S_{*}(X)$ with $(S_{*}X)_{n}=S_{n}(X)$ defined to be the free ${\mathcal{H}}$-sheaf generated by the elements of $X_{n}$ with $d_{i}$ in $S_{*}(X)$ taken to be the linear extensions of the face maps $d_{i}$ of $X$. We can also form the total face map: $d=\sum_{i=0}^{n}d_{i}:S_{n}(X)\rightarrow S_{n-1}(X)$ and then define the homology $H_{*}(X)=H_{*}(S_{*}(X),d)$ of the chain complex $(S_{*}(X),d)$ in the persistence topos $\widehat{{\mathcal{H}}}$. This follows the construction of the generalisation of the Barr-Beck cotriple homology as in [15].
Definition 7.4. Consider the category $(Set^{{\mathcal{H}}^{op}})^{\Delta_{+}^{op}}$ , i.e., the slice category where: (i) the objects are functors $\Delta_{+}^{op}\rightarrow Set^{{\mathcal{H}}^{op}}$; (ii) the morphisms are natural transformations between those functors; generalising semi-simplicial homology by substituting the topos $Set$ with the topos $Set^{{\mathcal{H}}^{op}}$. Denote by ${\mathcal{H}}$-sheaf any sheaf on the topos of persistence $\widehat{\mathcal{H}}=Set^{\mathcal{H}^{op}}$, that is, any element of the category of sheaves over ${\mathcal{H}}$. A simplicial ${\mathcal{H}}$-sheaf is a simplicial object $X$ in the category of sheaves over ${\mathcal{H}}$, i.e., $X:\Delta^{op}\rightarrow\widehat{\mathcal{H}}$ In this same order of ideas, a semi-simplicial ${\mathcal{H}}$-sheaf is a $\Delta$-set in $\widehat{\mathcal{H}}$, that is, $X:\Delta_{+}^{op}\rightarrow\widehat{\mathcal{H}}$
Definition 5.5. The category of locales is determined by complete Heyting algebras (as objects) and morphisms between them preserving finite $\wedge$ and arbitrary $\vee$. A sober space is a topological space $X$ such that every irreducible closed subset of $X$ has a unique point $P$ whose closure is all of $X$. A locale ${\mathcal{L}}$ is spatial (or topological) if each element of ${\mathcal{L}}$ can be expressed as a meet of prime elements.
