Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{U}$ and $\mathcal{V}$ be full additive subcategories of $\mathscr{C}$. We call $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ a cotorsion pair if it satisfies (i) $\mathrm{Ext}^{1}(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})=0$, (ii) $\mathscr{C}=\mathcal{U}\ast\mathcal{V}[1]$.
Definition 2.7. A pair of cotorsion pairs $(\mathcal{S},\mathcal{T}),(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ on $\mathscr{C}$ is called a twin cotorsion pair if it satisfies $\mathrm{Ext}^{1}(\mathcal{S},\mathcal{V})=0.$ Remark that this condition is equal to $\mathcal{S}\subseteq\mathcal{U}$, and also to $\mathcal{T}\supseteq\mathcal{V}$.
Definition 3.3.3. Given a quiver $D$, let $V_{L}:=V(D)$ and $E_{L}:=\{(0,e):e\in E(D)\}\cup\{(1,v,w):v,w\in V(D),\operatorname{edges}_{D}(v% ,w)=\emptyset\}.$ Define $\sigma_{L},\tau_{L}:E_{L}\to V_{L}$ by $\sigma_{L}(f):=\left\{\begin{array}[]{cc}\sigma_{D}(e),&f=(0,e),\\ v,&f=(1,v,w),\\ \end{array}\right.$ and $\tau_{L}(f):=\left\{\begin{array}[]{cc}\tau_{D}(e),&f=(0,e),\\ w,&f=(1,v,w).\\ \end{array}\right.$ Then, $L(D):=\left(V_{L},E_{L},\sigma_{L},\tau_{L}\right)$ is a quiver, the loading of $D$.
Definition 4.3. Given a quiver $G$, let $\kappa_{G}:\operatorname{indep}(G)\to V(G)$ by $\kappa_{G}(v):=v$, the usual inclusion of the independent vertices. Likewise, let $\lambda_{G}:E(G)\to E(G)$ be the identity function on $E(G)$. Then, there are unique quiver maps $\hat{\kappa}_{G}:I(\operatorname{indep}(G))\to G$ and $\hat{\lambda}_{G}:M(E(G))\to G$ such that $V\left(\hat{\kappa}_{G}\right)=\kappa_{G}$ and $E\left(\hat{\lambda}_{G}\right)=\lambda_{G}$. Let $\iota_{1,G}$ and $\iota_{2,G}$ be the canonical inclusions of $I(\operatorname{indep}(G))$ and $M(E(G))$, respectively, into $X(G)$. Then, there is a unique quiver map $p_{G}:X(G)\to G$ such that $p_{G}\circ\iota_{1,G}=\hat{\kappa}_{G}$ and $p_{G}\circ\iota_{2,G}=\hat{\lambda}_{G}$, the covering map of $G$.
Definition 2.1 (Quiver, [3, Definition 2.1]). A quiver is a quadruple $(V,E,\sigma,\tau)$, where $V,E\in\operatorname{Ob}(\mathbf{Set})$ are sets, and $\sigma,\tau\in\mathbf{Set}(E,V)$ are functions. Elements of $V$ are vertices, and $V$ the vertex set. Elements of $E$ are edges, and $E$ the edge set. The function $\sigma$ is the source map, and $\tau$ the target map. For $e\in E$, $\sigma(e)$ is the source of $e$, and $\tau(e)$ the target of $e$.
Definition 3.1.1. For a quiver $J$ and $v,w\in V(J)$, let $\operatorname{edges}_{J}(v,w):=\sigma_{J}^{-1}(v)\cap\tau_{J}^{-1}(w),$ the set of all edges in $J$ with source $v$ and target $w$. A quiver $J$ is loaded if for every $v,w\in V(J)$, $\operatorname{edges}_{J}(v,w)\neq\emptyset$.
Definition 4.1. Given a quiver $G$, a vertex $v\in V(G)$ is independent if $\sigma_{G}^{-1}(v)=\tau_{G}^{-1}(v)=\emptyset$. Define $\operatorname{indep}(G):=\{v\in V(G):v\textrm{ is independent}\},$ the set of all independent vertices in $G$. The explosion of $G$ is the quiver $X(G):=I(\operatorname{indep}(G))\coprod M(E(G)),$ the disjoint union of the independent set of $G$ with the edges of $G$ forced to be independent.
Definition 2.2 (Quiver map, [3, Definition 2.4]). Given quivers $G$ and $H$, a quiver homomorphism from $G$ to $H$ is a pair $\left(\phi_{V},\phi_{E}\right)$, where $\phi_{V}\in\mathbf{Set}\left(V_{G},V_{H}\right)$ and $\phi_{E}\in\mathbf{Set}\left(E_{G},E_{H}\right)$ satisfy $\phi_{V}\circ\sigma_{G}=\sigma_{H}\circ\phi_{E}$ and $\phi_{V}\circ\tau_{G}=\tau_{H}\circ\phi_{E}$. The function $\phi_{V}$ is the vertex map, and $\phi_{E}$ the edge map.
Definition 2.3 (Reflection quivers, [4, p. 20]). Fix a set $S$. (1) Let $\mathbf{0}_{S}:\emptyset\to S$ be the empty function to $S$. The independent set of vertices or empty quiver on $S$ is $I(S):=\left(S,\emptyset,\mathbf{0}_{S},\mathbf{0}_{S}\right),$ the quiver with vertex set $S$ and no edges. (2) Given $j=0,1$, let $\iota_{j}:S\to\{0,1\}\times S$ by $\iota_{j}(s):=(j,s)$ be the usual inclusions. The independent set of edges on $S$ is the quiver $M(S):=\left(\{0,1\}\times S,S,\iota_{0},\iota_{1}\right).$ (3) Given $j=0,1$, let $\pi_{j}:S^{2}\to S$ by $\pi_{1}(s,t):=s$ and $\pi_{2}(s,t):=t$ be the usual projections. The (directed) complete graph or full quiver on $S$ is the quiver $K(S):=\left(S,S^{2},\pi_{1},\pi_{2}\right).$ (4) Let $\mathbb{1}:=\{1\}$ and $\mathbf{1}_{S}:S\to\mathbb{1}$ be the constant function from $S$. The (directed) bouquet on $S$ is $B(S):=\left(\mathbb{1},S,\mathbf{1}_{S},\mathbf{1}_{S}\right),$ the quiver with edge set $S$ and one vertex.
Definition 15 (Generating Acyclic Cofibrations). The set $\bar{J}$ of generating acyclic cofibrations consists of the following $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$-multifunctors closed under pushouts, transfinite composition, and retracts: A1: Given a generating acyclic cofibration $K\hookrightarrow L$ of the model structure on $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ the induced multifunctors $G_{n}[K]\longrightarrow G_{n}[L]$ for each $n\geq 0$. A2: The $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$-functors ${\mathcal{I}}\longrightarrow{\mathcal{H}}$ viewed as multifunctors via $\Xi.$
Definition 5. Given a multicategory $\mathcal{P}$ with $\operatorname{obj}({\mathcal{P}}):=S$ and a set map $F_{0}:T\longrightarrow S$, we construct a pullback multicategory $F^{*}(\mathbb{\mathcal{P}})$ with object set $T$ whose operations are given by $F^{*}(\mathcal{P})(d_{1},\cdots,d_{n};d):=\mathcal{P}(Fd_{1},...,Fd_{n};Fd).$
Definition 3. Let ${\mathcal{P}}$ and $\operatorname{\mathtt{Q}}$ be two multicategories. A multifunctor $F:{\mathcal{P}}\rightarrow\operatorname{\mathtt{Q}}$ is essentially surjective if $[F]_{1}$ is essentially surjective as a functor of categories. We say that $F$ is full if for any sequence $p_{1},...,p_{n},p$ the function $F:{\mathcal{P}}(p_{1},...,p_{n};p)\rightarrow\operatorname{\mathtt{Q}}(Fp_{1},% ...,Fp_{n};Fp)$ is surjective. We say that $F$ is faithful if for any sequence $p_{1},...,p_{n},p$ the function $F:{\mathcal{P}}(p_{1},...,p_{n};p)\rightarrow\operatorname{\mathtt{Q}}(Fp_{1},% ...,Fp_{n};Fp)$ is injective. The multifunctor $F$ is called fully faithful if it is both full and faithful.
Definition 14 (Generating Cofibrations). The set $\bar{I}$ of generating cofibrations consists of the following $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$-multifunctors closed under pushouts, transfinite composition, and retracts: C1: Given a generating cofibration $K\hookrightarrow L$ in the model structure on $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ the induced multifunctors $G_{n}[K]\longrightarrow G_{n}[L]$ for each $n\geq 0$.4i.e. a cofibration of ${\mathcal{M}ulti}(\operatorname{\mathcal{C}})_{\{0,1,...,n\}}$ C2: the $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$-functors $\emptyset\longrightarrow{\mathcal{I}}$ viewed as $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$-multifunctors via $\Xi.$
Definition 4. Let $F:{\mathcal{P}}\rightarrow\operatorname{\mathtt{Q}}$ be a functor between two symmetric multicategories. We say that $F$ is an equivalence of multicategories if, and only if, $F$ is both fully faithful and essentially surjective.
Definition 3.9 ([34]). We define the triangulated category of matrix factorizations $\mathfrak{MF}_{\lambda}(Y,W)$ on $Y$ with a superpotential $W$ as the Verdier quotient ${\rm H}^{0}\mathfrak{DG}_{\lambda}(Y,W)/\mathfrak{Ac}_{\lambda}(Y,W).$
Definition 5.6. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a triangulated category. An object $E\in\mathcal{T}$ is called a classical generator of $\mathcal{T}$ if the smallest full triangulated subcategory $\mathcal{U}\subseteq\mathcal{T}$ that contains $E$ and is closed under taking direct summands (i.e. $A\in\mathcal{U}$ and $A=B\oplus C$ implies $B,C\in\mathcal{U}$) coincides with $\mathcal{T}.$
Definition 3.2. Let $(Y,W)$ be a Landau-Ginzburg model with $Y=\operatorname{Spec}A,$ we define a category $DB(Y,W)$ of D-branes of type B (B-branes) on $Y$ with the superpotential $W$ as the product $DB(Y,W):=\prod_{\lambda\in\mathbb{A}^{1}}\mathfrak{MF}_{\lambda}(Y,W).$
Definition 5.3 (Fukaya, Seidel). The Fukaya-Seidel category $\mathfrak{FS}(Y,\omega_{\mathbb{C}},W)$ is the $A_{\infty}$-category of twisted complexes over $\operatorname{Lag}_{vc}(X,\omega_{\mathbb{C}},W,\{\gamma_{i}\})$ or in this case it is the $A_{\infty}$-category of finite dimensional $A_{\infty}$-modules over $\operatorname{Lag}_{vc}(X,\omega_{\mathbb{C}},W,\{\gamma_{i}\}).$
Definition 2.2 (Homological Mirror Symmetry). We say that two sigma-models $(X,I,\omega_{\mathbb{C}})$ and $(X^{\vee},I^{\vee},\omega^{\vee}_{\mathbb{C}})$ are homologically mirror symmetric if we have equivalences of triangulated categories $\begin{array}[]{llll}a)&\mathbf{D}^{b}\bigl{(}\operatorname{coh}(X,I)\bigr{)}&% \cong&\mathbf{D}\mathfrak{Fuk}\bigl{(}X^{\vee},\omega^{\vee}_{\mathbb{C}}\bigr% {)}\\ b)&\mathbf{D}\mathfrak{Fuk}\bigl{(}X,\omega_{\mathbb{C}}\bigr{)}&\cong&\mathbf% {D}^{b}\bigl{(}\operatorname{coh}(X^{\vee},I^{\vee})\bigr{)}.\end{array}$
Definition 3.5. Let $(Y,W)$ be a Landau-Ginzburg model. We can define a category $DB(Y,W)$ of D-branes of type B on $Y$ with the superpotential $W$ as the product $DB(Y,W):=\prod_{\lambda\in\mathbb{A}^{1}}\mathbf{D}_{\text{sg}}(W^{-1}(\lambda% )).$
Definition 1.1 ([44]). Let $\mathcal{T}$ be an additive category. The structure of a triangulated category on $\mathcal{T}$ is defined by giving of the following data: a) an additive autoequivalence $[1]:\mathcal{T}\longrightarrow\mathcal{T}$ (it is called a shift functor or a translation functor), b) a class of exact (or distinguished) triangles: $X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle u}}{{\longrightarrow}}Y\stackrel{{\scriptstyle v}}{{% \longrightarrow}}Z\stackrel{{\scriptstyle w}}{{\longrightarrow}}X[1],$ which must satisfy the set of axioms Verdier T1–T4. T1. a) For each object $X$ the triangle $X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\operatorname{id}}}{{\longrightarrow}}X\longrightarrow 0% \longrightarrow X[1]$ is exact. b) Each triangle isomorphic to an exact triangle is exact. c) Any morphism $X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle u}}{{\longrightarrow}}Y$ can be included in an exact triangle $X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle u}}{{\longrightarrow}}Y\stackrel{{\scriptstyle v}}{{% \longrightarrow}}Z\stackrel{{\scriptstyle w}}{{\longrightarrow}}X[1].$ T2. A triangle $X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle u}}{{\longrightarrow}}Y\stackrel{{\scriptstyle v}}{{% \longrightarrow}}Z\stackrel{{\scriptstyle w}}{{\longrightarrow}}X[1]$ is exact if and only if the triangle $Y\stackrel{{\scriptstyle v}}{{\longrightarrow}}Z\stackrel{{\scriptstyle w}}{{% \longrightarrow}}X[1]\stackrel{{\scriptstyle-u[1]}}{{\longrightarrow}}Y[1]$ is exact. T3. For any two exact triangles and two morphisms $f,g$ the diagram below $\xymatrix{X\ar[r]^{u}\ar[d]_{f}\ar@{}[dr]|{\Box}&Y\ar[r]^{v}\ar[d]^{g}&Z\ar[r]% ^{w}\ar@{.>}[d]^{h}&X[1]\ar[d]^{f[1]}\\ X^{\prime}\ar[r]^{u^{\prime}}&Y^{\prime}\ar[r]^{v^{\prime}}&Z^{\prime}\ar[r]^{% w^{\prime}}&X^{\prime}[1].}$ can be completed to a morphism of triangles by a morphism $h:Z\to Z^{\prime}.$ T4. For each pair of morphisms $X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle u}}{{\longrightarrow}}Y\stackrel{{\scriptstyle v}}{{% \longrightarrow}}Z$ there is a commutative diagram $\begin{CD}X@>{u}>{}>Y@>{x}>{}>Z^{\prime}@>{}>{}>X[1]\\ \Big{\|}@V{v}V{}V@V{}V{w}V\Big{\|}\\ X@>{}>{}>Z@>{y}>{}>Y^{\prime}@>{w^{\prime}}>{}>X[1]\\ @V{}V{}V@V{}V{t}V@V{}V{u[1]}V\\ X^{\prime}@=X^{\prime}@>{r}>{}>Y[1]\\ @V{}V{r}V@V{}V{}V\\ Y[1]@>{x[1]}>{}>Z^{\prime}[1]\end{CD}$ where the first two rows and the two central columns are exact triangles.
Definition 5.1 (Seidel). The directed category of vanishing cycles $\operatorname{Lag}_{vc}(W,\{\gamma_{i}\})$ is an $A_{\infty}$-category over a coefficient ring $R$ with objects $L_{0},\dots,L_{r}$ corresponding to the vanishing cycles; the morphisms between the objects are given by the following rule ${\mathrm{H}}{\mathrm{o}}{\mathrm{m}}(L_{i},L_{j})=\begin{cases}CF^{*}(L_{i},L_% {j};R)=R^{|L_{i}\cap L_{j}|}&\mathrm{if}\ i<j\\ R\cdot id&\mathrm{if}\ i=j\\ 0&\mathrm{if}\ i>j;\end{cases}$ and the differential $m_{1},$ composition $m_{2},$ and higher order products $m_{k}$ $m_{k}:{\mathrm{H}}{\mathrm{o}}{\mathrm{m}}(L_{i_{0}},L_{i_{1}})\otimes\dots% \otimes{\mathrm{H}}{\mathrm{o}}{\mathrm{m}}(L_{i_{k-1}},L_{i_{k}})\to{\mathrm{% H}}{\mathrm{o}}{\mathrm{m}}(L_{i_{0}},L_{i_{k}})[2-k]$ are defined in terms of Lagrangian Floer homology inside $\Sigma_{*}.$
Definition 3.3. The triangulated category of singularities of $X$ is defined as the quotient $\mathbf{D}_{\text{sg}}(X):=\mathbf{D}^{b}(\operatorname{coh}X)\bigl{/}% \mathfrak{Perf}(X).$ When we have an action of an algebraic group $G$ on $Y,$ we can also consider an equivariant version of the triangulated category of singularities $\mathbf{D}_{\text{sg}}^{G}(X):=\mathbf{D}^{b}(\operatorname{coh}^{G}X)\bigl{/}% \mathfrak{Perf}^{G}(X).$
Definition 2.1. A geometric input for a sigma-model is a data of the following form $(X,I,\omega,B)$ that consists of a smooth manifold $X$ with a complex structure $I,$ an (1,1)-Kähler form $\omega$ and a real closed $2$-form $B$ which is called a B-field. For shortness we will also use the following combination $B+i\omega$ and denote it by $\omega_{\mathbb{C}}.$
Definition 3.7. A triangle $\underline{{\mathbb{E}}}{\to}\underline{{\mathbb{F}}}{\to}\underline{{\mathbb{% G}}}{\to}\underline{{\mathbb{E}}}[1]$ in ${\rm H}^{0}\mathfrak{DG}_{\lambda}(Y,W)$ is called an exact triangle if it is isomorphic to a standard triangle.
Definition 2.8. A Landau-Ginzburg model is a collection $(Y,I,\omega,B,W),$ where $Y$ is a smooth variety, $\omega$ is an (1,1)-Kähler form, $B$ is a closed real 2-form (B-field), and $W\colon Y\to\mathbb{A}^{1}$ is a regular function that is called a superpotential. We also can consider an action of an algebraic group $G$ on $Y$ such that the superpotential $W$ is semi-invariant.
Definition 5.5. Let $(Y,\omega_{\mathbb{C}},W)$ be a Landau-Ginzburg model. We define a category $DA(Y,\omega_{\mathbb{C}},W)$ of D-branes of type A (A-branes) on $Y$ with the superpotential $W$ as follows $DA(Y,\omega_{\mathbb{C}},W):=\mathbf{H}\mathfrak{FS}(Y,\omega_{\mathbb{C}},W)% \cong\mathbf{D}\mathfrak{FS}(Y,\omega_{\mathbb{C}},W)\cong\mathbf{D}^{b}(% \operatorname{mod}_{fd}-\operatorname{Lag}_{vc}(X,\omega_{\mathbb{C}},W,\{% \gamma_{i}\})).$
Definition 3.1. Let $E$ and $E^{\prime}$ be vector spaces, $C\subset E$ and $C^{\prime}\subset E^{\prime}$ be cones, and $P\subset E$ and $Q\subset E^{\prime}$ be polytopes. We define the tensor products as follows: $\displaystyle C\otimes C^{\prime}={\operatorname{cone}}\{(x\otimes y)\ |\ x\in C% ,\ y\in C^{\prime}\}\subset E\otimes E^{\prime},$ $\displaystyle P\otimes Q=\operatorname{conv}\big{(}\big{\{}(x\otimes y,x,y)\ |% \ x\in P,\ y\in Q\big{\}}\big{)}\subset\big{(}E\otimes E^{\prime}\big{)}\oplus E% \oplus E^{\prime}.$
Definition 2.1. A dg-algebra $A$ over $\mathbb{C}$ is compact if $A$ is perfect as a $\mathbb{C}$ module (in this special case this simply says that $A$ is equivalent to a finite dimensional vector space). A dg-algebra $A$ is smooth if $A$ is perfect as an $A-A$ bimodule.
Definition 3.1. We define $Pre(MF(\mathcal{A},w))$, to be the full subcategory of $mod(\mathcal{A}_{0})$ consisting of modules which are perfect over $\mathcal{A}$.
